			<section id="tribute-info">
				<h3 id="headline"> Timeline of Dr. Turing's life:
				</h3>
				<div>
				<ul>
					<li>
						<strong>1912</strong>
						Alan Mathison Turing was born in Maida Vale, London.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1927</strong>
						Alan furthered his love of science by reading Einstein whilst at Sherborne.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1934</strong>
						Alan graduates with distinction in Mathematics from King's College, Cambridge
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1938</strong>
						Alan goes to Princeton University to study mathematics and is awarded a PhD.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1939</strong>
						Alan is asked to join the governemnt Codes and Ciphers school and arrives the day after war is delcared.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1940</strong>
						Alan develops the Bombe with Gordon Welchman to decipher messages sent by the Germans using the Enigma machine.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1943</strong>
						Alan works with top people in the U.S. while visiting to share information on code breaking.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1945</strong>
						Alan is awarded the OBE for his wartime services.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1946</strong>
						Alan publishes a paper with the first design of a stored-program computer.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1949</strong>
						Alan is made deputy director of the Computing Labratory at Manchester University.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1950</strong>
						Alan publishes the famous paper 'Computer Machinery and Intelligence' in which he develops the Turing Test.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1951</strong>
						Alan is elected Fellow of the Royal Society, and also gives talks about Artificial Intelligence on the BBC.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1952</strong>
						Alan is arrested for gross indecency. He loses his security clearance and cannot work. He is offered chemical treatment instead of going to prison, this treatment makes him very unwell.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>1954</strong>
						Alan dies in his home. He is found poisoned with a half eaten apple next to him laced with cyanide.
					</li>
				</ul>
				</div>
				<h3>
				If you have time, go read more about his eventful life on his
				<a id="tribute-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Turing" target="_blank">Wikipedia page</a>.
		</main>
	</body>





